Starbucks Capstone Challenge¶

Introduction¶

This data set contains simulated data that mimics customer behavior on the Starbucks rewards mobile app. Once every few days, Starbucks sends out an offer to users of the mobile app. An offer can be merely an advertisement for a drink or an actual offer such as a discount or BOGO (buy one get one free). Some users might not receive any offer during certain weeks.

Not all users receive the same offer, and that is the challenge to solve with this data set.

Your task is to combine transaction, demographic and offer data to determine which demographic groups respond best to which offer type. This data set is a simplified version of the real Starbucks app because the underlying simulator only has one product whereas Starbucks actually sells dozens of products.

Every offer has a validity period before the offer expires. As an example, a BOGO offer might be valid for only 5 days. You'll see in the data set that informational offers have a validity period even though these ads are merely providing information about a product; for example, if an informational offer has 7 days of validity, you can assume the customer is feeling the influence of the offer for 7 days after receiving the advertisement.

You'll be given transactional data showing user purchases made on the app including the timestamp of purchase and the amount of money spent on a purchase. This transactional data also has a record for each offer that a user receives as well as a record for when a user actually views the offer. There are also records for when a user completes an offer.

Keep in mind as well that someone using the app might make a purchase through the app without having received an offer or seen an offer.

Example¶

To give an example, a user could receive a discount offer buy 10 dollars get 2 off on Monday. The offer is valid for 10 days from receipt. If the customer accumulates at least 10 dollars in purchases during the validity period, the customer completes the offer.

However, there are a few things to watch out for in this data set. Customers do not opt into the offers that they receive; in other words, a user can receive an offer, never actually view the offer, and still complete the offer. For example, a user might receive the "buy 10 dollars get 2 dollars off offer", but the user never opens the offer during the 10 day validity period. The customer spends 15 dollars during those ten days. There will be an offer completion record in the data set; however, the customer was not influenced by the offer because the customer never viewed the offer.

Cleaning¶

This makes data cleaning especially important and tricky.

You'll also want to take into account that some demographic groups will make purchases even if they don't receive an offer. From a business perspective, if a customer is going to make a 10 dollar purchase without an offer anyway, you wouldn't want to send a buy 10 dollars get 2 dollars off offer. You'll want to try to assess what a certain demographic group will buy when not receiving any offers.

Final Advice¶

Because this is a capstone project, you are free to analyze the data any way you see fit. For example, you could build a machine learning model that predicts how much someone will spend based on demographics and offer type. Or you could build a model that predicts whether or not someone will respond to an offer. Or, you don't need to build a machine learning model at all. You could develop a set of heuristics that determine what offer you should send to each customer (i.e., 75 percent of women customers who were 35 years old responded to offer A vs 40 percent from the same demographic to offer B, so send offer A).

Data Sets¶

The data is contained in three files:

  • portfolio.json - containing offer ids and meta data about each offer (duration, type, etc.)
  • profile.json - demographic data for each customer
  • transcript.json - records for transactions, offers received, offers viewed, and offers completed

Here is the schema and explanation of each variable in the files:

portfolio.json

  • id (string) - offer id
  • offer_type (string) - type of offer ie BOGO, discount, informational
  • difficulty (int) - minimum required spend to complete an offer
  • reward (int) - reward given for completing an offer
  • duration (int) - time for offer to be open, in days
  • channels (list of strings)

profile.json

  • age (int) - age of the customer
  • became_member_on (int) - date when customer created an app account
  • gender (str) - gender of the customer (note some entries contain 'O' for other rather than M or F)
  • id (str) - customer id
  • income (float) - customer's income

transcript.json

  • event (str) - record description (ie transaction, offer received, offer viewed, etc.)
  • person (str) - customer id
  • time (int) - time in hours since start of test. The data begins at time t=0
  • value - (dict of strings) - either an offer id or transaction amount depending on the record

'''
Clean the portfolio dataframe and return cleaned version. The cleaninign includes:
    *converting channels to be one column each
    *changing the duration to be hours
    *changing the ids to easier ids and rename to customer_id
arguments:
    portfolio: the portfolio dataframe
output:
    portfolio: the cleaned portfolio dataframe
    new_offer_ids: the mapping of old offer ids to new offer ids


'''
def clean_portfolio_df(portfolio):
    # clean portfolio ----- to be converted to method later on.
    #change the duraiton to be hours
    portfolio['duration_hours'] = portfolio['duration'] * 24
    portfolio.drop('duration',inplace=True,axis=1)

    #conver the channels to seperate columns
    portfolio['web'] = portfolio.apply(lambda x:0  if type(x['channels'])==float else (1 if 'web' in x['channels'] else 0) ,axis=1)
    portfolio['email'] = portfolio.apply(lambda x:0  if type(x['channels'])==float else (1 if 'email' in x['channels'] else 0) ,axis=1)
    portfolio['mobile'] = portfolio.apply(lambda x:0  if type(x['channels'])==float else (1 if 'mobile' in x['channels'] else 0) ,axis=1)
    portfolio['social'] = portfolio.apply(lambda x:0  if type(x['channels'])==float else (1 if 'social' in x['channels'] else 0) ,axis=1)
    portfolio.drop('channels',axis=1,inplace=True)

    #change the ids to be easier to read
    old_offer_ids = portfolio['id'].astype('category').cat.categories.tolist()
    new_offer_ids = {x:y for x,y in zip(old_offer_ids,list(range(1,len(old_offer_ids)+1)))} 
    portfolio['offer_id'] = portfolio['id'].map(new_offer_ids)
    portfolio.drop('id',axis=1,inplace=True)

    #reorder portfolio
    portfolio = portfolio[['offer_id','offer_type','difficulty','reward','duration_hours','web','email','mobile','social']]
    
    return portfolio, new_offer_ids


portfolio, new_offer_ids = clean_portfolio_df(portfolio)

'''
Clean the profile dataframe by doing the following:
    *change the ids to readable ids
    *change ids column to customer_id
    *introduce number of days since joining column
    *introduce customer_type (new,regular,loyal)
    *introduce year of join
    *introduce age group (young_adult,middle_age_adult,old_adult)
    *introduce income_range (low,mid,high)
    *keep track of the new ids and old ids of the records to drop
    *drop 118 years of age records
arguments:
    profile: profile dataframe
output:
    profile: the cleaned profile dataframe
    deleted_customer_ids: list of deleted customers
    new_customer_ids: mapping of old customer ids to new customer ids


'''

def clean_profile_df(profile):
    #change the ids to readable ids and change column name
    old_customer_ids = profile['id'].astype('category').cat.categories.tolist()
    new_customer_ids = {x:y for x,y in zip(old_customer_ids,list(range(1,len(old_customer_ids)+1)))} 
    # profile.replace(new_customer_ids,inplace=True)
    profile['customer_id'] = profile['id'].map(new_customer_ids)
    profile.drop('id',axis=1,inplace=True)
    # profile.rename(columns={'id':'customer_id'},inplace=True)

    #introduce year of join
    profile['year_joined'] = profile['became_member_on'].apply(lambda x:str(x)[:4])
    # introduce number of days since join
    date_today = date(2020,10,15)
    profile['days_as_member'] = profile['became_member_on'].apply(lambda x: date_today -  date(int(str(x)[:4]),
                                                                    int(str(x)[4:6]),int(str(x)[6:])))
    profile['days_as_member'] = profile['days_as_member'].apply(lambda x: x.days)
    #introduce customer type
    profile['customer_type'] = profile['days_as_member'].apply(lambda x: 'new' if x < 1095 else 
                                                               ('regular' if x < 2190 else 'loyal'))
    profile.drop('became_member_on',axis=1,inplace=True)
    # introduce age group
    profile['age_group'] = profile['age'].apply(lambda x: 'young_adult' if x < 40 else
                                                ('middle_age' if x < 60 else 'old'))
    # introduce income range
    profile['income_range'] = profile['income'].apply(lambda x: 'low' if x < 65000 else
                                                      ('mid' if x < 100000 else 'high'))
    #keep track of deleted ids 
    deleted_customer_ids = profile[profile['age'] == 118].customer_id.tolist()
    profile.drop(profile.loc[profile['age'] == 118].index,axis=0,inplace=True)

    #reorder columns 
    profile = profile[['customer_id','gender','age','age_group','income','income_range','year_joined'
                       ,'days_as_member','customer_type']]
    
    return profile,deleted_customer_ids,new_customer_ids

profile,deleted_customer_ids,new_customer_ids= clean_profile_df(profile)

'''
Clean the transcript dataframe by doing the following:
    *change person to customer id using new customer_ids
    *extract value to seperate columns (offer_id,reward,amount)
    *change offer_ids to the new ids
    *drop rows that are irrelevant since the customers were deleted
    *work on finding
    
        
arguments:
    transcript: transcript dataframe
    portfolio: portfolio dataframe
    new_customer_ids: mapping of old customer ids to new customer ids
    deleted_customer_ids: list of deleted customers
    new_offer_ids: mapping of old offer ids to new offer ids

output:
    transcript: cleaned transcript dataframe

'''


def clean_transcript_df(transcript = transcript,portfolio = portfolio,new_customer_ids = new_customer_ids
                        ,deleted_customer_ids = deleted_customer_ids,new_offer_ids = new_offer_ids):
    #change the person to readable customer ids and change column name
    # transcript.replace(new_customer_ids,inplace=True)
    transcript['customer_id'] = transcript['person'].map(new_customer_ids)
    transcript.drop('person',axis=1,inplace=True)

    # work on extracting the value column to seperate columns
    offers_ids           = transcript[transcript['event'].isin(['offer received','offer viewed'])].index.tolist()
    offers_completed_ids = transcript[transcript['event'] == 'offer completed'].index.tolist()
    transactions_ids     = transcript[transcript['event'] == 'transaction'].index.tolist()

    #add offer_id reward_recieved and amount spent columns
    transcript['offer id recieved and viewed'] = transcript.loc[offers_ids]['value'].apply(lambda x: x['offer id'])
    transcript['offer id completed'] = transcript.loc[offers_completed_ids]['value'].apply(lambda x: x['offer_id'])
    transcript['reward_received']   = transcript.loc[offers_completed_ids]['value'].apply(lambda x: x['reward'])
    transcript['amount'] = transcript.loc[transactions_ids]['value'].apply(lambda x: x['amount'])
    transcript['offer_id'] = transcript['offer id recieved and viewed'].fillna(transcript['offer id completed'])
    transcript.drop('offer id recieved and viewed',axis=1,inplace=True)
    transcript.drop('offer id completed',axis=1,inplace=True)
    transcript.drop('value',axis=1,inplace=True)

    #change the offer_ids to readable customer ids and change column name
    transcript['offer_id'] = transcript['offer_id'].map(new_offer_ids)

    #append offer_type to transcript dataframe
    transcript = pd.merge(transcript,portfolio[['offer_id','offer_type','duration_hours']],
                          how='left',left_on='offer_id',right_on='offer_id')

    #add offer_received_count offer_viewed_count and offer_completed_count
    transcript['offer_received_count']= np.nan
    transcript['offer_viewed_count']= np.nan
    transcript['offer_completed_count'] = np.nan
    transcript['offer_viewed_after_completion'] = np.nan
    
    return transcript


#Clean the transcript
transcript = clean_transcript_df()

'''
process the transcript dataframe to calculate the following:
*for each customer - how much was spent to complete offers and how much was not offer related
        which offers were received viewed and completed
        which offers were just viewed
        which offers were copmleted before viewing them

arguments:
    transcript: the transcript dataframe

output:
    transcript: transcript after processing
    money_spent_for_offers_dict: dictionary of the money spent to complete offers per user
    money_spent_without_offers_dict: dicitonary of the money spent not related to any offer per user
    
'''

def process_transcript_df(transcript):
    #create the dictionaries needed to cover money spent
    money_spent_for_offers_dict = dict()
    money_spent_without_offers_dict = dict()
    
    for customer in transcript['customer_id'].unique():   
        money_spent_no_offer = 0
        money_spent_post_offer = 0
        customer_df = transcript[transcript['customer_id'] == customer]
        # The customer did not recieve any offers
        if len(customer_df[customer_df['event'] == 'offer received'] ) <1:
            money_spent_no_offer = customer_df['amount'].sum()
            money_spent_without_offers_dict[customer] = money_spent_no_offer


        # The customer recieved at least one offer
        else :
            # get the indicies of the offer and offer ids recieved
            offer_ids = customer_df[customer_df['event'] == 'offer received'].offer_id
            offer_indecies = customer_df[customer_df['event'] == 'offer received'].index
            #create dictionaries to keep track of offers recieved viewed, viewed after completion, and completed
            offer_received_dict = dict()
            offer_viewed_dict = dict()
            offer_viewed_not_counted = dict()
            offer_completed_dict = dict()
            #this dict will keep track of the validity of each offer
            offer_limit_dict = dict()
            #set offer_recieved offer_viewed offer_completed to zeros
            for offer in offer_ids:
                offer_received_dict[offer] = 0
                offer_viewed_dict[offer] = 0
                offer_viewed_not_counted[offer]=0
                offer_completed_dict[offer] = 0
                #set offer_duration and offer_time to -1 if there is no offer
                offer_limit_dict[offer] = -1


            #loop over the customer rows
            for index,row in customer_df.iterrows():
                # check if this is a transaction
                if row['event'] == 'transaction':
                    # no offer is viewed hence the amount is spent without knowledge of offers
                    if(all(value == 0 for value in offer_viewed_dict.values())):
                        money_spent_no_offer += row['amount']
                    # all offers are already completed hence money spent is not realted to offers
                    elif (offer_completed_dict == offer_viewed_dict):
                        money_spent_no_offer += row['amount']
                    # the offers are already expired (passed their timelimit)
                    elif ((np.array(list(offer_limit_dict.values())) > row['time']).sum() == 0):
                        money_spent_no_offer += row['amount']
                    # This spending is within offer timelimit
                    else:
                        money_spent_post_offer += row['amount']

                # the offer recieved case
                elif row['event'] == 'offer received':
                    offer_received_dict[row['offer_id']] += 1
                    # capture the timelimit of the offer
                    offer_limit_dict[row['offer_id']] = row['time'] + row['duration_hours']

                # the offer viewed case
                elif row['event'] == 'offer viewed':
                    # the condition where offer is completed without viewing it
                    if(offer_completed_dict[row['offer_id']] > offer_viewed_dict[row['offer_id']]):
                        offer_viewed_not_counted[row['offer_id']] += 1
                    # the condition where offer is viewed after expiry of offer validity
                    elif(offer_viewed_dict[row['offer_id']] > offer_limit_dict[row['offer_id']]):
                        offer_viewed_not_counted[row['offer_id']] += 1
                    # count the offer is viewed
                    else:
                        offer_viewed_dict[row['offer_id']] += 1

                # the offer completed case
                elif row['event'] == 'offer completed':
                    offer_completed_dict[row['offer_id']] += 1

            #add money spent to dictionaries. this will be used later to see how much customer 
            #spent pre and post offers
            money_spent_without_offers_dict[customer] = money_spent_no_offer
            money_spent_for_offers_dict[customer] =  money_spent_post_offer

            for offer_index in offer_indecies:
                # add the offer count to the dataframe
                offer_id = customer_df.loc[offer_index,'offer_id']
                transcript.at[offer_index,'offer_received_count'] = offer_received_dict[offer_id]
                transcript.at[offer_index,'offer_viewed_count'] = offer_viewed_dict[offer_id]
                transcript.at[offer_index,'offer_completed_count'] = offer_completed_dict[offer_id]
                transcript.at[offer_index,'offer_viewed_after_completion'] = offer_viewed_not_counted[offer_id]  
        
    return transcript,money_spent_for_offers_dict,money_spent_without_offers_dict

#process the transcript dataframe and assign it to df to keep the transcript for reference
df,money_spent_for_offers_dict,money_spent_without_offers_dict = process_transcript_df(transcript)

'''
clean the transcript further after processing renaming some columns and dropping irrelevant ones and deleting
all rows releted to deleted customer ids. 

argument:
    df: the processed transcript dataframe
    deleted_customer_ids: the list of deleted customers
    
output:
    df: the cleaned and processed transcript dataframe

'''

def clean_transcript_post_processing(df=df,deleted_customer_ids=deleted_customer_ids):
    # creating a new dataframe to analyze from the transcript dataframe
    df = df[df['event'] == 'offer received']
    df.drop_duplicates(subset=['customer_id','offer_id'],inplace=True)
    df.rename(columns={'offer_received_count':'received','offer_viewed_count':'viewed',
                       'offer_completed_count':'completed','offer_viewed_after_completion':'viewed_late',
                       'reward_received':'reward'},inplace=True)
    df.drop(['event','time','amount','reward','offer_type','duration_hours'],axis=1,inplace=True)
    df = df[['customer_id','offer_id','received','viewed','completed','viewed_late']]
    #drop the customers that do not have any information about (the 118 years of age)
    df = df[~ df['customer_id'].isin(deleted_customer_ids)]
    return df

df = clean_transcript_post_processing()

#drope some fields that I will not use in the modelling
df_master.drop(['age','income','customer_id','days_as_member','year_joined'],axis=1,inplace=True)
# df_master.drop('customer_id',axis=1,inplace=True)
#convert gender to numbers M - 1 F -2 and O - 3
df_master['gender'] = df_master['gender'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == 'M' else (2 if x == 'F' else 3))
#convert age groups to number format young_adult=1 middle_age=2 and old=3
df_master['age_group'] = df_master['age_group'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == 'young_adult' 
                                                      else (2 if x == 'middle_age' else 3))
#convert income range to number format low = 1 mid=2 and high =3
df_master['income_range'] = df_master['income_range'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == 'low' 
                                                            else (2 if x == 'mid' else 3))
#convert customer type to number format new = 1 regular =2 loyal = 3
df_master['customer_type'] = df_master['customer_type'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == 'new' 
                                                              else (2 if x == 'regular' else 3))
#conver offer type to number format bogo = 1 discount = 2 informational =3
df_master['offer_type'] = df_master['offer_type'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == 'bogo' 
                                                           else (2 if x == 'discount' else 3))
#scale the duration hours reward and difficulty values since they are widley distributed
scaler = MinMaxScaler()
features = ['duration_hours', 'reward', 'difficulty']
# features = ['age','income','days_as_member','duration_hours','reward','difficulty','money_with_offers',
#            'money_without_offers']
df_master[features] = scaler.fit_transform(df_master[features])

In [95]:
'''
prints the classification report for the predicted value vs test value.
arguments:
    classification_name: name of the classifier
    y_pred: the predicted value
    y_test: the test value

'''
def print_scoring_report(classification_name,y_pred,y_test):
    labels = ['viewed','completed']
    y_test2 = np.array(y_test)
    y_pred2 = np.array(y_pred)
    class_dict={}

    for label in range(len(labels)):
        y_test_label = y_test2[:, label]
        y_pred_label = y_pred2[:, label]
        class_dict[labels[label]] = classification_report(y_pred=y_pred_label, y_true=y_test_label)
        print("The accuracy for label {} using {} is: {}".format(labels[label],classification_name,
                                                                    accuracy_score(y_test_label,y_pred_label)))

        
    for label, matrix in class_dict.items():
        print("Classificaiton report for label {} using {}:".format(label,classification_name))
        print(matrix)

'''
create a multioutput classifier and then fit it and predict the y value.
finally print the score of the classifier.
arguments:
    classifier_type: pass the classifier that you are using in the multioutput classifier
output:
    y_pred: the predicted y value

'''
def predict_values(classifier_type):
    classifier = MultiOutputClassifier(estimator=classifier_type,n_jobs=-1)
    classifier.fit(x_train,y_train)
    y_pred = classifier.predict(x_test)
#     print("The score of the classifier is ", classifier.score(x_test,y_test))
#     print("The score of the classifier on training data is ", classifier.score(x_train,y_train))
    return y_pred
